english:
  title: Memorial Against Welcoming the Yuan Emissary
  author: Jung Mong-ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your Majesty, I have heard that those who would govern the realm must first establish a resolute plan. Without such clarity, doubt poisons the hearts of men, and doubt brings calamity upon all things.

    Our eastern kingdom stands alone beyond the sea. Since our great founder arose in the twilight of Tang and conducted our relations through propriety, we have always honored the rightful authority of the realm. When the Yuan fell and the Ming rose to embrace all under heaven, my late lord perceived the mandate of heaven and sent envoys bearing tribute. The Emperor graciously received us, bestowed upon us the rank of prince, and for six years have our gifts and tributes flowed back and forth.

    When the present reign began, the traitor Kim Eui seized the moment of the Ming emissary's passage, murdered him on the road, and fled to the remnant Yuan. With their surviving princes, he plotted to enthrone Shenwang. He killed the emissary, betrayed his sovereign—such treachery demands justice. The Crown should have proclaimed his crimes before heaven and earth, sought his punishment through proper channels. Yet our state has done nothing. Worse still, we sent Minister Kim Seo to offer tribute northward, while General O Gye-nam slew three men of Dingliao garrison—companions of Kim Eui who never even reached the garrison, yet remain unpunished.

    Now a Yuan envoy arrives, and the court speaks of honoring him with ceremony at the border, saying this will "prevent the north from taking offense and delay their assault." But consider: The Yuan, having lost their realm, come seeking merely to eat their fill and prolong their miserable existence. What they call "installing a lord" is merely self-interest. If we refuse them, we demonstrate our strength. If we receive them, we embolden their arrogance. Thus what claims to delay war actually hastens it.

    I hear their proclamation accuses us of great rebellion, then pardons us as an afterthought. We are innocent—what crime requires pardon? If the court honors their emissary and sends him home, every subject of this realm will bear the name of traitor though guilty of nothing. How can this be made known across the land? Can any loyal servant endure such dishonor?

    Moreover, when Ming first learned of Kim Eui, they already harbored suspicion. If we now fail to punish him and are known to have dealings with the Yuan, they will certainly believe we killed their emissary and conspired with the enemy. Should Ming then send an army to demand justice, with forces advancing by water and land, what answer could our state possibly offer? What appears to delay a minor threat would actually summon the armies of all under heaven.

    The court's silence on this matter speaks volumes. The officials feared Ming's rebuke and secretly conspired with Kim Eui to sever our ties to the great power. An Si-gi's suicide was evidence of this very guilt. His death should have been followed by swift resolution to satisfy the people's righteous anger, yet silence persists. The realm grows restless; change looms.

    I humbly beseech Your Majesty to act with decisive wisdom: Detain the Yuan emissary, confiscate their edict, bind O Gye-nam and Zhang Zi-wen and all who traveled with Kim Eui, and send them to Ming's capital. Thus what was murky shall become clear without need of explanation. Then, accord with Dingliao garrison, gather forces, and await the moment for change. Let word spread that we march northward, and the Yuan remnants will withdraw their traces and flee far away. Thus shall our kingdom's fortune know no end.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Kim Eui: A historical traitor who murdered a Ming emissary and defected to the remnant Yuan forces during early Joseon'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Shenwang (瀋王): A prince of the Yuan dynasty, whose installation as a puppet ruler was part of the Yuan remnant''s political schemes'
  - key: ''
    value: 'An Si-gi (安師琦): A historical figure implicated in conspiracy with Kim Eui; his suicide confirmed his guilt'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dingliao garrison (定遼衛): A Ming military installation near the Joseon border'
  - key: ''
    value: This memorial represents Jung Mong-ju's urgent plea for decisive action against both treachery at home and diplomatic appeasement that he saw as disastrous
